thi poem, though published abroade fifte year ago, whe it ha excited considerabel attention, seem almost unknown to the english  literary world. and y it is the earliest known attempt, in any vernacular dialect of modern europe, to produce an epic poem; and far from being a dull and tedious imitation of some greek or latin examples,—like most modern epics,—i an original gothic performance; and if there be in me any spark|sparke of poetic feeling, i have no hesitation in affirming, that any poet, of any age, might have be proud to produce such a work, whil the counry which gave him birth might well be proud of him in return. i know there ar tastes, called classical, which will turn away in digust whe they ar told that thi poem consist of two fabulous adventures, not very artificially connected, except by the person of the hero,—and that these episodes, which relate to hitorical tradition of the north, ar rath|rath|rather unskilfully inserted. but i think such classical scholar as have a skueamish repugnance to all gothic productions, should remember that, whe they settle themselv down in the little circle of the ancient world, they have banished themselv from the modern, and, consekuently, have made their opinion on such a subject of very little importance. hence, without calling that artificial which is rude, or that masterly which is childish, whether of ancient or modern date, i will merely observe that beowulf, the gothic hero of the poem, combats, in the prime of hi life, with grendel and hi mother, two  goblins, who ar the foe of hrothgar, king of denmark; and in hi old age fight with steorc-heort, the fiery dragon, which, during a thousand years, ha brooded on unprofitabel gold; and in thi encouner, though victorious lose hi life. now, it is evident that such a tale may be told in a very absurd manner, but it is ekually clear that it may also be embodied in a very lofty and interesting strain; and for my own part i have no desire for the converse of any man wh