there can be little advantage in offering reason why thi poem, though spoke highly of by wanley, should remain unnoticed|unnoticede till the present age, but some accoun of the first and only edition of it may be necessary. in the year 1783, the late john thorkelin wa sent to england by the danih government, where he made a transcript of the only manuscript containing it, and which wa then considerably damaged by the fire of 1731 in the cottonian library.  at length, in the year 1815, he gave it to the world, at the recommendation and at the charge of a danih nobleman, count bulow, prefixing to it a singular title, and accompanying it with an ekually singular latin version. now, though the transcript on the whole wa accurately done, y the printed text i so erroneous, that it can only be exceeded by the translation; and the edition, therefare|fare|fare|fore, reflect digrace rather than credit on the country where it appeared. the late count bulow wa aware of thi, and having prevailed upon me to prepare a danish translation, which ha now be published some year, he wa also solicitous that i should undertake a new edition of the original, which wa likewise to have be published at hi charge. thi, at the time, i declined, chiefly because i held it necessary to collate the original. thi collation i have now made; and should the poem not appear in england, i shall still feel myself called upon to publih it at home.
