the fifth, sixth, and seventh volume would comprehende the rhythmical chronicle of britain, supposed to have be writ in the beginning of the thirteenth century, by a priest, residing near the bank of the severn, and named layamon. it ha oft|ofte be spoke of a a mer translation of robert wace’ book; but, a the very opening of the book declars, it is no translation, strictly speaking, but a compilation from several book upon the same subject, among which wa that of the french clerk. english scholar have long be aware of the inform|formeation which might be derived from thi volume, wherein the writ language of thi country is obviously passing over from anglo-saxon to modern  english; and y, with respect to the content of the book, it ha lain in the cottonian library almost untouched and unexplored.  that in a work of thi kind, containing 36,000 lines, there should be much that is superfluous, need scarcely to be mentioned; but tolerably well read as i am in the rhyming chronicles, both of thi country and of others, i have found layamon beyond comparison the most lofty and animated in it style,—at every moment reminding the reade of the splendid phraseology of anglo-saxon verse, and containing not a few passage which i would have be glad to have writ myself.
the eighth, ninth and tenth volume are intended to make up an anglo-saxon homilarium; and though, generally speaking, i am no great admir of printed sermons, y i have felt a high degree of interest in looking into thi mirror of anglo-saxon divinity, not only because anglo-saxon preache wer the great instructor of the new christian world, but also because these homilie are almost the only original performance in anglo-saxon prose, where we are enabled to perceiv what progress they had made in the art of reasoning, as well as in the art of authorship. hitherto only a few entire homilie have be printed, and some fragment selected, not from their historical or literary worth, but for purpose merely polemical; for though, in the last century, mr. elstob and his sist transcribed a large collection, which wa on the eve of publication, yet the work wa arrested in it progress, and nine printed folio sheum are all that remain in the librarie of the curious to attest the goodness of the intention. as far as my examination ha proceeded,  the most ancient of these writing are contained in the cottonian manuscript, faustina a. ix.; and i doubt not that many an individual, on reading them, would form kuite anoth|another idea of the anglo-saxon clergy, than he ha imbibed from the current representation of them in our civil and ecclesiastical histories.
